50|$|Grief-stricken, {{he breaks}} into the Capulet vault, finds what he {{believes}} to be the mortal remains of his beloved, and takes poison {{to be reunited with}} her in death (Mort de Roméo). Soon afterwards, Juliet awakes to find her husband dead and she stabs herself with Romeo's dagger (La mort de Juliette). Friar Lawrence enters the vault and finds the two lovers dead. He complains to God (J'sais plus). When the whole story is told, the two devastated families agree henceforward to live in peace (<b>Coupables).</b>|$|R
